1772378516684388	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyhQk		item.create	bn-7phd	{"description":"When two workspaces modify the same file (e.g., src/main.rs), merging the second workspace after the first silently overwrites the first workspace's changes with no warning, no conflict detection, and no error. The overlap command correctly identifies the risk as 'high' before merging, but the merge engine itself does not check for or prevent this. This is the 'stale workspace reversion hazard' and is the most dangerous behavior in the tool -- silent data loss with no recovery path (the overwritten content from the first merge is gone). Repro: (1) create conflict-1, conflict-2 at same epoch. (2) Both modify src/main.rs differently. (3) maw ws merge conflict-1 --destroy succeeds. (4) maw ws merge conflict-2 --destroy also succeeds, silently replacing conflict-1's version. Expected: merge should fail or warn when a workspace modifies files that have changed since its epoch.","kind":"bug","labels":["sim-test"],"size":"m","title":"Merge silently overwrites conflicting files from stale workspaces","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:1M-BWFOEWvUP5eX9FaI0AjB7wi_1NdJ70-tPF7Blpro
1772378524534887	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyhgk		item.create	bn-2ge6	{"description":"maw ws diff <workspace> returns empty output (exit 0) when the workspace has uncommitted new files or modifications. The diff only shows changes that have been git-committed. This is misleading because (a) the merge engine works on uncommitted file state, not committed state, and (b) a user/agent checking 'what changed in this workspace' before merging gets no output. The inconsistency between diff (committed-only) and merge (working directory) is confusing. Users have to know to commit before diffing, which is an unnecessary ceremony. Repro: (1) maw ws create test. (2) echo 'hi' > ws/test/new.txt. (3) maw ws diff test -> empty. (4) cd ws/test && git add -A && git commit -m x. (5) maw ws diff test -> shows the change.","kind":"bug","labels":["sim-test"],"size":"s","title":"ws diff shows nothing for uncommitted changes"}	blake3:EPHGTPPIukcXlLRyEGrtUlp1ornDwuIYKzmuvSsnW7w
1772378529742897	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyhwk		item.create	bn-2axt	{"description":"Running 'maw ws conflicts <name>' on a workspace that has already been destroyed gives: 'Error: prepare phase failed: PREPARE: HEAD not found for workspace conflict-2: spawn git: No such file or directory (os error 2)'. The real issue is the workspace does not exist, but the error message talks about 'spawn git' which is confusing. Expected: 'Error: workspace conflict-2 does not exist' or similar.","kind":"bug","labels":["sim-test"],"size":"xs","title":"ws conflicts on destroyed workspace gives misleading spawn git error"}	blake3:ksc78MGE1NzwhPuqWil2zqdJvzaxb8pyPgobys7X1Qc
1772378537456748	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyiAk		item.create	bn-3v88	{"description":"Every workspace that is created leaves behind refs/manifold/head/<name> and (if merged/destroyed) refs/manifold/recovery/<name>/* refs permanently. After the rapid create/destroy test of 5 workspaces, 5 head refs and 0 recovery refs remained. Over a long-lived project with many agent workspaces, this will accumulate unboundedly. There is no 'maw gc' or 'maw prune' command visible. maw doctor does not flag stale refs. Consider: (1) cleaning head refs on destroy when no changes exist, (2) adding a gc/prune command for old recovery refs, (3) having maw doctor report accumulated ref count.","kind":"task","labels":["sim-test"],"size":"s","title":"Stale refs accumulate indefinitely with no GC mechanism"}	blake3:V0Ijt9P1_eKh6YBVZoHNkmL2Ilx1GRjsj0LkwhpZB8M
1772378544683731	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyiQk		item.create	bn-21a3	{"description":"maw ws merge works on working directory state (uncommitted files are picked up and merged). But maw ws sync requires all changes to be committed, refusing with 'has uncommitted changes that would be lost by sync'. And maw ws diff only shows committed changes. This creates three different mental models for what counts as 'changes': merge sees uncommitted files, sync requires commits, diff only shows commits. For agent workflows, the merge behavior (working directory) is the most useful, and sync/diff should match it. At minimum, the inconsistency should be documented.","kind":"bug","labels":["sim-test"],"size":"s","title":"Inconsistency: merge accepts uncommitted changes but sync requires committed state"}	blake3:I7eCxIpIo4mzOInswusV7HJvWMPOWjNXu2T2YKh5fYM
1772378550620654	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyigk		item.create	bn-3qeh	{"description":"maw status shows '[WARN] Non-default workspaces: 2' with a list of names, but does not annotate which ones are stale vs fresh. The user has to run 'maw ws status' or 'maw ws list' to see staleness. Since staleness is a critical signal for agents (stale workspaces risk reversion on merge), maw status should show the stale annotation inline, e.g., '- active-ws (stale)' like maw ws list does.","kind":"task","labels":["sim-test"],"size":"xs","title":"maw status does not show stale workspace status"}	blake3:Pai0w87B_6f-UdUHHgpL-XMcGNaPzwYRf9K9hysC8DM
1772378559132899	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyiwk		item.create	bn-1zdc	{"description":"When running 'maw ws merge no-changes --destroy' on a workspace with zero changes, the merge correctly reports 'No changes detected' and 'Nothing to merge', but the workspace is NOT destroyed despite --destroy being passed. The output says 'Workspaces were not destroyed' which is technically informative, but the user explicitly asked to destroy. If I create a workspace, realize I don't need it, and try to merge+destroy in one shot, the workspace stays alive. The user then has to separately run 'maw ws destroy no-changes'. Consider: either destroy the workspace even when there are no changes (respecting the explicit --destroy flag), or at minimum suggest 'maw ws destroy no-changes' in the output.","kind":"bug","labels":["sim-test"],"size":"xs","title":"No-change merge leaves workspace alive despite --destroy flag"}	blake3:3NUpdZvVFFfNFFd9nBNcBvO5tg8QK--Bjr_3xYmCtbE
1772380229355521	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyjAk		item.comment	bn-7phd	{"body":"ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS:\n\nThe merge engine has a blind spot for stale workspaces. It detects conflicts between workspaces in the SAME merge (shared paths in partition_by_path), but never compares workspace changes against the epoch delta (what changed between the workspace's base epoch and the current epoch).\n\nFlow that causes silent overwrite:\n1. Epoch at E0. Workspaces A and B created (both based on E0).\n2. Both modify main.rs.\n3. merge A --destroy → epoch advances to E1 (A's main.rs in E1).\n4. merge B --destroy → B is the only source, main.rs is 'unique' (1 workspace). B's version overwrites A's. No conflict detected.\n\nKey code path:\n- collect_snapshots (src/merge/collect.rs:140) diffs each workspace against ITS OWN base epoch\n- partition_by_path (maw-core/merge/partition.rs:182) only sees paths touched by workspaces in THIS merge\n- build_merge_commit (maw-core/merge/build.rs:200) reads the CURRENT epoch tree, then applies workspace Upserts on top — silently overwriting epoch changes\n\nMissing piece: no comparison between workspace changes and the epoch delta (files changed between workspace base epoch and current epoch).\n\nWhy tests missed it: every test in build_phase.rs uses the same epoch for all workspaces. No test covers stale-workspace merge.\n\nWHERE TO FIX: in run_pipeline (src/merge/build_phase.rs:323), between collect_snapshots and partition_by_path. Inject synthetic PatchSet entries representing the epoch delta so that the partition sees overlapping files as shared paths, and the existing resolve/diff3 machinery handles the rest.\n\nPROPOSED FIX (jj-style three-way merge):\nWhen a workspace's base epoch != current epoch, compute the epoch delta (files changed between base and current). For any file in BOTH the epoch delta and the workspace's changes, run a three-way merge: base=workspace's base epoch version, ours=current epoch version, theirs=workspace version. If diff3 resolves cleanly, apply merged result. If not, report conflict (same as multi-workspace conflicts today). This reuses all existing conflict infrastructure."}	blake3:XSjBX5AOJN1MLIvsyLnEHR1UMCdDeZee1W16eQ5d4kw
